RULE CONFLICT: ORIGINAL SEQUENTIAL SCOAP VS MIN/MAX PARALLEL-TIME RULE
=====================================================================

1. Core claim
-------------

The two recurrences agree on one thing:

  Take the minimum across alternative input assignments that can justify
  the target output value.

They differ inside each one of those justifying assignments:

  Original SCOAP:
    add the controllabilities of all inputs that must be forced together

  Teacher's min/max rule:
    take the maximum of the input times for all inputs that must be ready
    together

So the real difference is:

  SCOAP = min of sums
  min/max rule = min of maxes

This means they are not the same metric.


2. Formal definition of the original SCOAP rule
-----------------------------------------------

Let J_v(z) be the set of all input assignments that force gate output z to
the target value v.

Goldstein's definition of output controllability is:

  controllability of z=v
    = minimum, over all justifying assignments j in J_v(z),
      of the sum of the input controllabilities required by j,
      plus the cell depth term

In [GT80], this is stated in equivalent form: output controllability is found
by taking the minimum, over all justifying input assignments, of the sum of
the required input controllabilities and then adding the cell-depth term.
Source: [GT80], p. 191.

For sequential controllability, the same paper says the only difference from
the combinational measure is where the depth term is counted:

  - combinational cells have sequential depth 0
  - sequential cells have sequential depth 1

So across ordinary combinational gates in sequential SCOAP, you do not add 1
at every logic level. You add 1 only when the path crosses a flip-flop or
other sequential element. That point is part of the formal definition, not a
special classroom shortcut. Source: [GT80], p. 191.


3. What the teacher's min/max rule is actually measuring
--------------------------------------------------------

The teacher's rule can be written as:

  T_v(z) = min over j in J_v(z) of
           [ max of the required input times inside j ]

Interpretation:

  - If a justification needs all listed inputs at once, and those inputs can
    be prepared in parallel, the completion time is controlled by the
    slowest one -> max(...)
  - If there are several alternative justifications, the earliest one wins
    -> min(...)

Important:

  This min/max recurrence is not the original SCOAP recurrence.

Inference from [GT80]:

  Goldstein's sequential controllability is a cost-style estimate based on
  adding required control effort, while the min/max rule behaves like an
  ideal parallel completion-time estimate. This inference is consistent with
  the paper's warning that the actual number of time frames needed can be
  less than the sequential controllability estimate when parallelism is
  exploited. Source: [GT80], p. 191.


4. Why sum appears in SCOAP
---------------------------

Under the original definition, each justifying assignment is treated as a set
of control requirements that must all be established together.

If a gate output requires:

  a=1 and b=1

then the cost of that justification is:

  cost = SC1(a) + SC1(b)

because both requirements belong to the same justification cube.

If instead the target output can be justified by either:

  a=0
  or
  b=0

then the output controllability is:

  min( SC0(a), SC0(b) )

because either single-input justification is enough.

That "sum within one justification, min across alternative justifications"
structure is the core SCOAP idea. Source: [GT80], p. 191.


5. Derived gate rules
---------------------

Note on citation:

  The OR-gate formulas are written explicitly in [GT80], Eqs. (1)-(4),
  p. 192. The AND, NAND, and NOR formulas follow by duality and inversion
  from the same definition. XOR and XNOR follow by directly listing their
  justifying assignments J_v(z).


5.1 Simple 1-input cells
------------------------

BUF
  Sequential SCOAP:
    SC0(z) = SC0(a)
    SC1(z) = SC1(a)

  Min/max time rule:
    T0(z) = T0(a)
    T1(z) = T1(a)

NOT
  Sequential SCOAP:
    SC0(z) = SC1(a)
    SC1(z) = SC0(a)

  Min/max time rule:
    T0(z) = T1(a)
    T1(z) = T0(a)


5.2 AND-family and OR-family cells
----------------------------------

+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| Gate | Sequential SCOAP                     | Min/max parallel-time rule           |
+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| AND  | SC0(z) = min(SC0(a), SC0(b))         | T0(z) = min(T0(a), T0(b))            |
|      | SC1(z) = SC1(a) + SC1(b)            | T1(z) = max(T1(a), T1(b))            |
+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| NAND | SC0(z) = SC1(a) + SC1(b)            | T0(z) = max(T1(a), T1(b))            |
|      | SC1(z) = min(SC0(a), SC0(b))         | T1(z) = min(T0(a), T0(b))            |
+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| OR   | SC0(z) = SC0(a) + SC0(b)            | T0(z) = max(T0(a), T0(b))            |
|      | SC1(z) = min(SC1(a), SC1(b))         | T1(z) = min(T1(a), T1(b))            |
+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| NOR  | SC0(z) = min(SC1(a), SC1(b))         | T0(z) = min(T1(a), T1(b))            |
|      | SC1(z) = SC0(a) + SC0(b)            | T1(z) = max(T0(a), T0(b))            |
+------+--------------------------------------+--------------------------------------+

Reason:

  - AND=1 and OR=0 require all listed inputs simultaneously
    -> SCOAP uses +
    -> parallel-time rule uses max

  - AND=0 and OR=1 can be justified by any one suitable input
    -> both metrics use min across alternatives


5.3 XOR and XNOR
----------------

For XOR:

  J_0(z) = { a=0,b=0 ; a=1,b=1 }
  J_1(z) = { a=0,b=1 ; a=1,b=0 }

Therefore:

  Sequential SCOAP:
    SC0(z) = min( SC0(a)+SC0(b), SC1(a)+SC1(b) )
    SC1(z) = min( SC0(a)+SC1(b), SC1(a)+SC0(b) )

  Min/max time rule:
    T0(z) = min( max(T0(a),T0(b)), max(T1(a),T1(b)) )
    T1(z) = min( max(T0(a),T1(b)), max(T1(a),T0(b)) )

For XNOR:

  J_0(z) = { a=0,b=1 ; a=1,b=0 }
  J_1(z) = { a=0,b=0 ; a=1,b=1 }

Therefore:

  Sequential SCOAP:
    SC0(z) = min( SC0(a)+SC1(b), SC1(a)+SC0(b) )
    SC1(z) = min( SC0(a)+SC0(b), SC1(a)+SC1(b) )

  Min/max time rule:
    T0(z) = min( max(T0(a),T1(b)), max(T1(a),T0(b)) )
    T1(z) = min( max(T0(a),T0(b)), max(T1(a),T1(b)) )


5.4 n-input extension
---------------------

The same pattern extends directly:

  - If the target output value requires all listed inputs together:
      SCOAP uses sum(...)
      min/max rule uses max(...)

  - If the target output value can be justified by any one of several input
    choices:
      both metrics use min(...)

So for an n-input AND:

  SC1(z) = sum of all required SC1(input_i)
  T1(z)  = max of all required T1(input_i)

And for an n-input OR:

  SC0(z) = sum of all required SC0(input_i)
  T0(z)  = max of all required T0(input_i)


6. Your Z node
--------------

Suppose Z is the output of an AND gate, and its two inputs have:

  left input:  [0,1]
  right input: [1,2]

meaning:

  left input has SC0/T0 = 0 and SC1/T1 = 1
  right input has SC0/T0 = 1 and SC1/T1 = 2

To force Z=1 on an AND gate, both inputs must be 1.

So:

  Original sequential SCOAP:
    SC1(Z) = SC1(left) + SC1(right)
           = 1 + 2
           = 3

  Teacher's min/max rule:
    T1(Z) = max( T1(left), T1(right) )
          = max(1,2)
          = 2

Conclusion:

  Both answers are internally consistent, but they answer different
  questions.

  - 3 is the SCOAP-style cumulative control cost
  - 2 is the ideal parallel readiness time


7. Bottom-line wording for an exam or viva
------------------------------------------

If you need a short statement:

  "Original sequential SCOAP is a min-of-sums controllability measure.
  The teacher's rule is a min-of-maxes parallel-time measure. They coincide
  on which justifications are possible, but they differ on how they score
  a justification that requires multiple inputs simultaneously."


